      <section class="tg-section" id="introduction">
        <h2 class="tg-section__heading">How to Use This Guide</h2>
        <p>Hebrews calls itself "a word of exhortation" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Hebrews 13:22">13:22</a>) —
        the same phrase used of a synagogue homily in <a class="ref" data-ref="Acts 13:15">Acts 13:15</a>.
        It was a sermon before it was a letter, designed to be heard as a continuous argument. Every
        chapter builds on the last. The writer is not cataloguing truths; he is making a case —
        a relentless, OT-saturated case that Jesus is better than everything the congregation
        might return to.</p>
        <p>The danger he is addressing is not heresy but <em>drift</em>: a community tempted
        to step back from costly allegiance to Jesus, pulled by social pressure, persecution,
        or nostalgia for the old covenant's visible forms. His answer is not to argue them
        into compliance but to show them — with overwhelming scriptural evidence — what they
        would be abandoning.</p>
        <p>Each chapter below includes: <strong>The Argument</strong> (what move the writer is
        making here and how it fits the overall case), <strong>OT Background boxes</strong>
        (the original context of every major quotation, read before Hebrews deploys it), and
        <strong>Discussion Questions</strong>.</p>

